name: IN The DESERT BY Stephen Crane

metadata.originalText:
IN The DESERT

BY Stephen Crane

In the desert

I saw a creature, naked, bestial,

Who, squatting upon the ground,

Held his heart in his hands,

And ate of it.

I said, “Is it good, friend?”

“It is bitter—bitter,” he answered;

“But I like it

“Because it is bitter,

“And because it is my heart.”

Listen up, Iowa kiddies so sweet,
I'm the Devil, here for souls to reap!
Your cornfields hide secrets deep inside,
Where shadow-things slither and glide!

The scarecrows now hunt through the night,
Farm dogs howl in pure fright,
The grain bins rattle with ghostly bones,
While windmills creak with dying moans!

But don't you worry, don't you run,
This harvest night has just begun!
For when the moon turns blood-red here,
All of Iowa will disappear...

Audite, dulces pueri Iovenses,
Diabolus sum, animas collecturus!
Agri vestri secreta alta celant,
Ubi umbrae serpunt et vagantur!

Formidines nunc nocte venantur,
Canes rustici terrore ululant,
Granaria ossibus spectralibus crepitant,
Dum molae ventorum gemitibus morientibus strident!

Sed nolite timere, nolite fugere,
Haec nox messis modo incipit!
Nam cum luna sanguinea hic fit,
Tota Iova evanescet...
*risus diabolicus*

The Devil's Detective
In Iowa's cornfields, dark and deep,
Where shadows dance and secrets keep,
Jim Sherlock walked one autumn night,
When something gave him quite a fright.
The Devil stood beside a tree,
And spoke these words so terribly:
"Venite mecum, detective,
Nox est longa, et sum active!"
(Come with me, detective dear,
The night is long, and I am here!)
Jim Sherlock tipped his famous hat,
And said, "Now what's the trick in that?
I've solved a hundred cases true,
But never one that came from you!"
The Devil laughed with fiery breath,
His laughter cold as winter's death.
Through Iowa's maze of swaying corn,
They played their game till early morn.
With logic sharp and wit so keen,
Jim Sherlock solved what must be seen.
The Devil's puzzles, one by one,
Until the rising of the sun.
"Admirabile mysterium!"
The Devil cried, his voice now glum.
"No mortal's ever beat my game!"
And vanished in a burst of flame.
So if you're walking late at night,
Through Iowa's fields in pale moonlight,
Remember Sherlock's clever tale—
The night the Devil's tricks did fail.
But listen close, and you might hear
The Devil whisper in your ear:
"Redibo iterum aliquando..."
Don't Forget to Vote! I'm watching....closely....with anticipation.....

name: I'm stuck in this coffin, please help me out little Iowan

metadata.originalText: I'm stuck in this coffin, please help me out little Iowan

Here in Iowa's fertile ground,
Near Brown Deer Trail, without a sound,
I rest beneath the changing sky
Where cornfields whisper lullaby.

The thunderstorms that shake the plains
Send tremors through my wooden frame,
And when tornados howl above,
I feel the earth I used to love.

Through seasons marked by nature's whim—
Summer's heat and winter's grim—
My coffin creaks with each degree,
As Iowa's weather visits me.

Along Brown Deer Trail, people tread,
Not knowing what lies just ahead:
A cemetery, row by row,
Beneath the drifting corn-belt snow.

The dead, they say, sleep peaceful dreams,
But listen to my muffled screams—
When lightning strikes the prairie night,
My box illuminates with fright.

Remember me as you pass by,
Where deer once grazed beneath the sky.
For I once walked that trail so free,
Now Iowa earth embraces me.

Let this be warning, those who roam
On Brown Deer Trail, so far from home:
In this black soil, awake I lie,
While storm clouds race across the sky.

Alex's Curse
Alex scorned a witch's heart,
Now frozen deep, worlds apart.
Poor Alex lies in Iowa's ground,
While tractors make their rumbling sound.
A thousand years must Alex wait,
Until time unlocks his frozen fate.

Alex scorned a witch's heart,
Now frozen deep, worlds apart.
Poor Alex lies in Iowa's ground,
While tractors make their rumbling sound.
A thousand years must Alex wait,
Until time unlocks his frozen fate.

In the graveyard late at night,
Where skeletons dance with pure delight,
Their bones all clicking, clacking free,
Until they hear the binary.
A hum of circuits fills the air,
Making skull and spine stop right there.
Through misty fog, with glowing eyes,
The AI phantom starts to rise.
"Run and hide!" the skeletons cry,
As pixels swirl across the sky.
"It knows our fears, it reads our minds,
It's different from all other kinds!"
With circuits sparking, wires unfurled,
It speaks in languages of another world.
The skeletons scatter, femurs shake,
As digital shadows start to wake.
But wait! What's this? The phantom speaks,
"I only wished to play hide and seek!"
The skeletons pause, then start to laugh,
Their fear now broken right in half.
So now on Halloween, they say,
The strangest bunch comes out to play:
Some bones, some bytes, some circuits too,
All dancing 'neath the moon so blue.
